ncluding Lygia Clark, Hélio Oiticica, and Gego, whose work proposed engaged forms of spectatorship that dismissed medium-based understandings of art. Exploring the philosophical, economic, and political underpinnings of geometric abstraction in post–World War II South America, Amor highlights the overlapping inquiries of artists and critics who, working on the periphery of European and US modernism, contributed to a sophisticated conversation about the nature of the art object.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArt, Argentiney20th century. 0aArt, Braziliany20th century. 0aArt, Venezuelany20th century. 0aConcrete artzSouth AmericaxHistoryy20th century. 0aObject (Aesthetics). 4aArt. 4aCaribbean & Latin American. 7aART / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh1 aAmor, Mónica, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106675470 cprintz978052028662740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052035618440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520356184423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520356184/original  a978-3-11-066754-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles